What's Genuinely Missing

4. Session token distribution
There's no explicit mechanism to distribute the session token to non-DM players. Players receive config via MSG_CONFIG but the session token isn't part of the config blob. If a player device joins after the broadcast window, or the token is set after config is sent, it will silently drop all game packets due to token mismatch.

5. typeId uniqueness not enforced
GameManager::registerGame() doesn't check for duplicate typeId values. Two registered games with the same typeId would cause silent radio filtering conflicts — the wrong TotemRunner might activate.
Design Flaws

1. Totem assignment encoding is a hack
_totemAssignment[] in GameSetupMenu encodes two conceptually different things in one byte: values < GenericTotemRoles::COUNT (3) = generic role, values ≥ 3 = totemVar index offset by 3. This is fragile — adding a new generic role breaks all existing totemVar indices silently. It should be a struct: { bool isNamed; uint8_t value; }.

2. Enlight via global pointer
Games declare extern Enlight* enlightPtr (e.g., GameFreeForAll.cpp line ~47). The pointer is initialized in the sketch, but nothing prevents a game from dereferencing it before initialization, and there's zero compile-time safety. Enlight should be injected into GameRunner::begin() or into the game callbacks as a parameter.

3. Player ID space vs team map mismatch
_teamMap in GameRunner is size 16 (PlayerDefs::MAX_PLAYER_ID). RadioPacket.senderId is a uint8_t (0–255). Players with IDs ≥16 are silently placed on team 0. This isn't enforced at the radio layer, and PlayerDefs::playerNames only has meaningful entries for IDs 0–9 anyway ("Unknown" for 10–15). The implicit maximum of ~9 real players is never stated or checked.

4. Player ID 0 ("00-None") is ambiguous
ID 0 is used as "None"/unassigned in TotemVar::id (default = 0), but is technically a valid RadioPacket.senderId. If a device accidentally transmits with ID 0, it could corrupt score slots. Should be an explicit sentinel (0xFF or similar) for "unassigned totem."

5. Message type collisions with no registry
Game-specific message types (e.g., MSG_LIT = 0x10) are locally defined per game file. There's nothing stopping two games from using the same value. Since typeId filtering should prevent cross-game collisions at runtime, this is mostly a code hygiene issue — but it will cause confusion when debugging and could break if someone runs two game sessions with adjacent typeIds.

6. Config blob has no version or length prefix
game_apply_config() deserializes the blob by fixed offset arithmetic, assuming the blob was produced by the current firmware version. There's no version byte, no total-length field, no checksum. A DM running a different firmware version than players will apply garbage config silently (the function returns false only on typeId mismatch or buffer-too-short, not on schema mismatch).

7. Discovery window is too rigid
The 3-second ROSTER_WINDOW_MS is hardcoded. The DM can't extend it if they know a player is still booting. There's also no re-broadcast from players during the window — they depend on the timing of their own MSG_ROSTER broadcast. If a player boots at second 2.9, they're missed.


